{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nThe core deliverable of the epic: an `in_progress` ticket should carry the coding-agent\nsession that STARTED it, end-to-end (written on the STATUS event AND folded into compiled\nstate), additively — without disturbing `assignee` / `author`, and byte-identical to today\nwhen no session id is present. Recording without folding produces no observable outcome, so\nboth halves ship together.\n\n## What\n- **Write (`src/rebar/_commands/txn.py`).** In `claim_core` and `transition_core`, when the\n  event is an `open -> in_progress` STATUS, call the shared `resolve_session_id()` (story\n  6014) via a small `_stamp_session(status_data)` helper; when it returns non-None, add\n  `data[\"session\"]`. When None, OMIT the key entirely so the event bytes are identical to the\n  pre-feature path. Stamp on ANY `open -> in_progress` STATUS — the `claim` command AND a\n  bare `transition <id> open in_progress` (including the parent-first cascade) — not just\n  `claim`.\n- **Fold (`src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py`).** In `process_status`, a\n  `_fold_claimed_session(state, data)` helper sets `state[\"claimed_session\"] = data[\"session\"]`\n  when the applied status is `in_progress` and a `session` key is present. It is invoked ONLY\n  in the two branches that APPLY this event's status — the normal-update branch and the\n  fork-WINNER branch — and NEVER in the branch where the existing chain wins, so a losing\n  concurrent claim never overwrites the winner's session (epic advisory G6/T8). The value\n  persists thereafter (mirrors `assignee`); it is not cleared on later transitions.\n- **Forward/back-compat.** `data[\"session\"]` is an additive data key; a reducer build without\n  the fold ignores unknown data keys (it only reads `data.get(\"status\")` / `current_status`),\n  so an older clone tolerates the event. Absent-session events are byte-identical to today.\n\n## Scope\n- IN: the write stamp (both cores) + the reducer fold + unit/integration tests (present,\n  absent/byte-identical, bare-transition, fork-winner gating, forward-compat tolerance).\n- OUT: snapshot/compaction default + pretty read surface + MCP outputSchema (S3 / 199b);\n  `OPENCODE_SESSION_ID`/`CODEX_THREAD_ID` + harness provenance (S5 / c557); capture hooks\n  (S4 / S6). The shared resolver itself is story 6014 (already landed as this stack's base).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Claiming with a session env var set records `claimed_session` in compiled state.\n      Proof: `pytest tests/unit/test_claimed_session.py -k claim_records -q`.\n- [ ] Claiming with NO session env var set records nothing AND the STATUS event carries no\n      `session` key (byte-identical no-session path). Proof:\n      `pytest tests/unit/test_claimed_session.py -k absent -q` asserts `claimed_session` is\n      absent from state AND `\"session\" not in` the written STATUS event's `data`.\n- [ ] A bare `transition <id> open in_progress` records it too (cascade parents included).\n      Proof: `pytest tests/unit/test_claimed_session.py -k transition -q`.\n- [ ] Fork-winner gating: when two competing `open -> in_progress` STATUS events carry\n      DIFFERENT session ids, compiled `claimed_session` equals the lexical-UUID WINNER's\n      session (never the loser's). Proof:\n      `pytest tests/unit/test_claimed_session.py -k fork -q` replays both events in BOTH\n      orders and asserts the winner's session each time.\n- [ ] Forward-compat: `process_status` folds a STATUS whose `data` carries both `session` and\n      an arbitrary UNKNOWN extra key without error, and the unknown key does not enter state\n      (proxy for an older clone tolerating the additive key). Proof:\n      `pytest tests/unit/test_claimed_session.py -k forward_compat -q`.\n\n## Depends on\n- S1 (shared resolver `resolve_session_id`) — landed as the base of this stack."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783540582843711001,"uuid":"f942ec3f-91dc-4d50-af77-cb72f203425d"}